04495nam a22006015i 9780520383401DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020053128  a(OCoLC)1302164012  a97805203834017 a10.1525/97805203834012doi  a(DE-B1597)618113  a(OCoLC)1301548883  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDR545b.O8513 2021 4aDR545b.O8513 2021 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a943.6/031092aB2231 aTimisoara, Osman of, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPrisoner of the Infidels :bThe Memoir of an Ottoman Muslim in Seventeenth-Century Europe /cOsman of Timisoara; ed. by Giancarlo Casale. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tList of maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Transcription from Ottoman Turkish -- tA Note on the Translation -- tIntroduction: On Being Osman -- t1 Surrender -- t2 Ransom -- t3 Crime and Punishment -- t4 Death and Resurrection -- t5 Respite -- t6 Bonds of Love -- t7 To the Capital -- t8 A Friend in Need -- t9 An Unexpected Turn of Events -- t10 Into the Lion’s Den -- t11 Grifters -- t12 To the Border -- t13 The End -- tAppendix: The Main Characters in Osman’s Narrative -- tNotes -- tIndex of People -- tIndex of Places0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVictor Hugo meets Papillon in this effervescent memoir of war, slavery, and self-discovery, told with aplomb and humor in its first English translation. A pioneering work of Ottoman Turkish literature, Prisoner of the Infidels brings the seventeenth-century memoir of Osman Agha of Timişoara—slave, adventurer, and diplomat—into English for the first time. The sweeping story of Osman’s life begins upon his capture and subsequent enslavement during the Ottoman–Habsburg Wars. Adrift in a landscape far from his home and traded from one master to another, Osman tells a tale of indignation and betrayal but also of wonder and resilience, punctuated with queer trysts, back-alley knife fights, and elaborate ruses to regain his freedom. Throughout his adventures, Osman is forced to come to terms with his personhood and sense of belonging: What does it mean to be alone in a foreign realm and treated as subhuman chattel, yet surrounded by those who see him as an object of exotic desire or even genuine affection? Through his eyes, we are treated to an intimate view of seventeenth-century Europe from the singular perspective of an insider/outsider, who by the end his account can no longer reckon the boundary between Islam and Christendom, between the land of his capture and the land of his birth, or even between slavery and redemption.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAustro-Turkish War, 1716-1718vPersonal narratives, Turkish. 0aPrisoners of warzRomaniazTimiṣoaravBiography. 0aPrisoners of warzRomaniazTimișoaravBiography. 0aPrisoners of warzRomaniazTimișoaravBiography. 0aPrisoners of warzTurkeyvBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aCasale, Giancarlo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520383401?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520383401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520383401/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles